{"parentUuid":"f4b40e7c-bf9b-4bb0-b02b-a3fc36a1c530","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"aba4c59c369d45698","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01HHLTUw8xGWNtoREu1Nwtfx","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_015k5ZnmJA1txEWizwyxyu9M","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"sed -n '8,30p' /tmp/alphaevolve.txt; echo \"=== DIST PIPELINE ===\"; sed -n '470,500p' /tmp/alphaevolve.txt; echo \"=== PROMPT SAMPLER 2.2 ===\"; sed -n '252,300p' /tmp/alphaevolve.txt","description":"Read abstract, distributed pipeline, prompt sampler"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2215,"cache_read_input_tokens":21702,"output_tokens":245,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2215},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":245,"cache_read_input_tokens":21702,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2215,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2215,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcG27nnNLpVPACmykJatA","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"aa487a40-57ab-4247-bbf3-0cf14b8af52e","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:40.338Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"aa487a40-57ab-4247-bbf3-0cf14b8af52e","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"aba4c59c369d45698","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_015k5ZnmJA1txEWizwyxyu9M","type":"tool_result","content":"In this white paper, we present AlphaEvolve, an evolutionary coding agent that substantially enhances\ncapabilities of state-of-the-art LLMs on highly challenging tasks such as tackling open scientific problems\nor optimizing critical pieces of computational infrastructure. AlphaEvolve orchestrates an autonomous\npipeline of LLMs, whose task is to improve an algorithm by making direct changes to the code. Using\nan evolutionary approach, continuously receiving feedback from one or more evaluators, AlphaEvolve\niteratively improves the algorithm, potentially leading to new scientific and practical discoveries. We\ndemonstrate the broad applicability of this approach by applying it to a number of important computational problems. When applied to optimizing critical components of large-scale computational\nstacks at Google, AlphaEvolve developed a more efficient scheduling algorithm for data centers, found\na functionally equivalent simplification in the circuit design of hardware accelerators, and accelerated the training of the LLM underpinning AlphaEvolve itself. Furthermore, AlphaEvolve discovered\nnovel, provably correct algorithms that surpass state-of-the-art solutions on a spectrum of problems\nin mathematics and computer science, significantly expanding the scope of prior automated discovery\nmethods (Romera-Paredes et al., 2023). Notably, AlphaEvolve developed a search algorithm that found a\nprocedure to multiply two 4 × 4 complex-valued matrices using 48 scalar multiplications; offering the\nfirst improvement, after 56 years, over Strassen’s algorithm in this setting. We believe AlphaEvolve and\ncoding agents like it can have a significant impact in improving solutions of problems across many areas\nof science and computation.\n\n1. Introduction\nDiscovering new high-value knowledge, such as making a novel scientific discovery or developing a commercially valuable algorithm, generally requires a prolonged process of ideation,\nexploration, backtracking on unpromising hypotheses, experimentation, and validation.\nThere has been much recent interest in using large language models (LLMs) to automate\nsignificant parts of this process. Hopes of success here are driven by the breathtaking power of\nrecent LLMs [32, 76], which can enhance their capabilities using test-time compute, and the\n=== DIST PIPELINE ===\nAlphaEvolve is implemented as an asynchronous computational pipeline (using the asyncio\nPython library) in which many computations are run concurrently, with each computation\nblocking (waiting) whenever its next step relies on the result of another, yet unfinished\ncomputation. More specifically, the asynchronous pipeline comprises a controller, LLM\nsamplers, and evaluation nodes. The entire pipeline is optimized for throughput (rather than\nthe speed of any one particular computation), in order to maximize the number of ideas that\ncan be proposed and evaluated within a specific overall computation budget.\n8\n\n\fAlphaEvolve: A coding agent for scientific and algorithmic discovery\n\n⟨𝑚, 𝑛, 𝑝⟩\n⟨2, 4, 5⟩\n⟨2, 4, 7⟩\n⟨2, 4, 8⟩\n⟨2, 5, 6⟩\n⟨3, 3, 3⟩\n⟨3, 4, 6⟩\n⟨3, 4, 7⟩\n⟨3, 4, 8⟩\n⟨3, 5, 6⟩\n⟨3, 5, 7⟩\n⟨4, 4, 4⟩\n⟨4, 4, 5⟩\n⟨4, 4, 7⟩\n⟨4, 4, 8⟩\n⟨4, 5, 6⟩\n⟨5, 5, 5⟩\n\nbest known [reference] AlphaEvolve\n33 [42]\n=== PROMPT SAMPLER 2.2 ===\nAs AlphaEvolve leverages SOTA LLMs, it supports various types of customization and providing\nlong contexts as part of the primary evolution prompt. This prompt comprises multiple\npreviously discovered solutions sampled from the program database, as well as system\ninstructions on how to propose changes to a particular solution. Beyond these key ingredients,\nusers can further tailor prompts to their specific needs in different ways, such as the following.\n• Explicit context: details about the problem being solved, such as fixed human-written\ninstructions, equations, code snippets, or relevant literature (e.g., pdf files).\n• Stochastic formatting: template placeholders with human-provided alternatives for\nincreased diversity, instantiated using probability distributions provided in a separate\nconfig file.\n• Rendered evaluation results: usually this will include a program, the result of executing\nthat program, and the scores assigned by the evaluate function.\n• Meta prompt evolution: instructions and context suggested by the LLM itself in an\nadditional prompt-generation step, co-evolved in a separate database analogous to the\nsolution programs.\n2.3. Creative generation\nTo drive the evolutionary procedure, AlphaEvolve leverages the capabilities of SOTA LLMs,\nwhose principal role is to digest information about previously developed solutions and\npropose new, diverse ways to improve the solutions. Although AlphaEvolve is model-agnostic,\nin ablations we observe that AlphaEvolve performs increasingly better as the underlying LLM\nimproves (see Section 4).\n5\n\n\fAlphaEvolve: A coding agent for scientific and algorithmic discovery\n\n# EVOLVE-BLOCK START\n\"\"\"Image classification experiment in jaxline.\"\"\"\n\nAct as an expert software developer. Your task is to iteratively\nimprove the provided codebase. [...]\n- Prior programs\n\nimport jax\n...\n# EVOLVE-BLOCK-END\n\nPreviously we found that the following programs performed well\non the task at hand:\n\n...\n\ntop_1_acc: 0.796; neg_eval_log_loss: 0.230; average_score: 0.513\n\n# EVOLVE-BLOCK-START\nclass ConvNet(hk.Module):\ndef __init__(self, num_classes): ...\ndef __call__(self, inputs, is_training): ...\n\n\"\"\"Image classification experiment in jaxline.\"\"\"","is_error":false}]},"uuid":"22a5348d-675f-4d64-8800-9df55d569faf","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:41.508Z","toolUseResult":{"stdout":"In this white paper, we present AlphaEvolve, an evolutionary coding agent that substantially enhances\ncapabilities of state-of-the-art LLMs on highly challenging tasks such as tackling open scientific problems\nor optimizing critical pieces of computational infrastructure. AlphaEvolve orchestrates an autonomous\npipeline of LLMs, whose task is to improve an algorithm by making direct changes to the code. Using\nan evolutionary approach, continuously receiving feedback from one or more evaluators, AlphaEvolve\niteratively improves the algorithm, potentially leading to new scientific and practical discoveries. We\ndemonstrate the broad applicability of this approach by applying it to a number of important computational problems. When applied to optimizing critical components of large-scale computational\nstacks at Google, AlphaEvolve developed a more efficient scheduling algorithm for data centers, found\na functionally equivalent simplification in the circuit design of hardware accelerators, and accelerated the training of the LLM underpinning AlphaEvolve itself. Furthermore, AlphaEvolve discovered\nnovel, provably correct algorithms that surpass state-of-the-art solutions on a spectrum of problems\nin mathematics and computer science, significantly expanding the scope of prior automated discovery\nmethods (Romera-Paredes et al., 2023). Notably, AlphaEvolve developed a search algorithm that found a\nprocedure to multiply two 4 × 4 complex-valued matrices using 48 scalar multiplications; offering the\nfirst improvement, after 56 years, over Strassen’s algorithm in this setting. We believe AlphaEvolve and\ncoding agents like it can have a significant impact in improving solutions of problems across many areas\nof science and computation.\n\n1. Introduction\nDiscovering new high-value knowledge, such as making a novel scientific discovery or developing a commercially valuable algorithm, generally requires a prolonged process of ideation,\nexploration, backtracking on unpromising hypotheses, experimentation, and validation.\nThere has been much recent interest in using large language models (LLMs) to automate\nsignificant parts of this process. Hopes of success here are driven by the breathtaking power of\nrecent LLMs [32, 76], which can enhance their capabilities using test-time compute, and the\n=== DIST PIPELINE ===\nAlphaEvolve is implemented as an asynchronous computational pipeline (using the asyncio\nPython library) in which many computations are run concurrently, with each computation\nblocking (waiting) whenever its next step relies on the result of another, yet unfinished\ncomputation. More specifically, the asynchronous pipeline comprises a controller, LLM\nsamplers, and evaluation nodes. The entire pipeline is optimized for throughput (rather than\nthe speed of any one particular computation), in order to maximize the number of ideas that\ncan be proposed and evaluated within a specific overall computation budget.\n8\n\n\fAlphaEvolve: A coding agent for scientific and algorithmic discovery\n\n⟨𝑚, 𝑛, 𝑝⟩\n⟨2, 4, 5⟩\n⟨2, 4, 7⟩\n⟨2, 4, 8⟩\n⟨2, 5, 6⟩\n⟨3, 3, 3⟩\n⟨3, 4, 6⟩\n⟨3, 4, 7⟩\n⟨3, 4, 8⟩\n⟨3, 5, 6⟩\n⟨3, 5, 7⟩\n⟨4, 4, 4⟩\n⟨4, 4, 5⟩\n⟨4, 4, 7⟩\n⟨4, 4, 8⟩\n⟨4, 5, 6⟩\n⟨5, 5, 5⟩\n\nbest known [reference] AlphaEvolve\n33 [42]\n=== PROMPT SAMPLER 2.2 ===\nAs AlphaEvolve leverages SOTA LLMs, it supports various types of customization and providing\nlong contexts as part of the primary evolution prompt. This prompt comprises multiple\npreviously discovered solutions sampled from the program database, as well as system\ninstructions on how to propose changes to a particular solution. Beyond these key ingredients,\nusers can further tailor prompts to their specific needs in different ways, such as the following.\n• Explicit context: details about the problem being solved, such as fixed human-written\ninstructions, equations, code snippets, or relevant literature (e.g., pdf files).\n• Stochastic formatting: template placeholders with human-provided alternatives for\nincreased diversity, instantiated using probability distributions provided in a separate\nconfig file.\n• Rendered evaluation results: usually this will include a program, the result of executing\nthat program, and the scores assigned by the evaluate function.\n• Meta prompt evolution: instructions and context suggested by the LLM itself in an\nadditional prompt-generation step, co-evolved in a separate database analogous to the\nsolution programs.\n2.3. Creative generation\nTo drive the evolutionary procedure, AlphaEvolve leverages the capabilities of SOTA LLMs,\nwhose principal role is to digest information about previously developed solutions and\npropose new, diverse ways to improve the solutions. Although AlphaEvolve is model-agnostic,\nin ablations we observe that AlphaEvolve performs increasingly better as the underlying LLM\nimproves (see Section 4).\n5\n\n\fAlphaEvolve: A coding agent for scientific and algorithmic discovery\n\n# EVOLVE-BLOCK START\n\"\"\"Image classification experiment in jaxline.\"\"\"\n\nAct as an expert software developer. Your task is to iteratively\nimprove the provided codebase. [...]\n- Prior programs\n\nimport jax\n...\n# EVOLVE-BLOCK-END\n\nPreviously we found that the following programs performed well\non the task at hand:\n\n...\n\ntop_1_acc: 0.796; neg_eval_log_loss: 0.230; average_score: 0.513\n\n# EVOLVE-BLOCK-START\nclass ConvNet(hk.Module):\ndef __init__(self, num_classes): ...\ndef __call__(self, inputs, is_training): ...\n\n\"\"\"Image classification experiment in jaxline.\"\"\"","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"aa487a40-57ab-4247-bbf3-0cf14b8af52e","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"22a5348d-675f-4d64-8800-9df55d569faf","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"aba4c59c369d45698","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01YVJVuEDUym3GXq8peNQimh","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have comprehensive primary-source material from both the DeepMind blog and the white paper PDF. Here are my findings.\n\n---\n\n# AlphaEvolve (Google DeepMind, 2025) — Architecture: Cited, Falsifiable Claims\n\nTwo primary sources, both DeepMind:\n- **BLOG** = DeepMind blog post: https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/\n- **PAPER** = DeepMind white paper PDF (\"AlphaEvolve: A coding agent for scientific and algorithmic discovery\", Novikov et al.): https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf\n\n## The LLM ensemble (which models, and why two)\n\n1. **AlphaEvolve uses an ensemble of exactly two specific Gemini models.** PAPER §2.3, \"Models used\": *\"AlphaEvolve employs an ensemble of large language models. Specifically, we utilize a combination of Gemini 2.0 Flash and Gemini 2.0 Pro.\"* (Source: PAPER)\n\n2. **The ensemble exists to trade throughput against quality.** PAPER §2.3: *\"This ensemble approach allows us to balance computational throughput with the quality of generated solutions.\"* (Source: PAPER)\n\n3. **Flash is the breadth/throughput model.** PAPER §2.3: *\"Gemini 2.0 Flash, with its lower latency, enables a higher rate of candidate generation, increasing the number of ideas explored per unit of time.\"* The blog states it more compactly: Flash *\"maximizes the breadth of ideas explored.\"* (Sources: PAPER; BLOG)\n\n4. **Pro is the depth/quality model providing occasional breakthroughs.** PAPER §2.3: *\"Concurrently, Gemini 2.0 Pro, possessing greater capabilities, provides occasional, higher-quality suggestions that can significantly advance the evolutionary search and potentially lead to breakthroughs.\"* Blog: Gemini Pro *\"provides critical depth with insightful suggestions.\"* (Sources: PAPER; BLOG)\n\n5. **The stated optimization goal of the mix.** PAPER §2.3: *\"This strategic mix optimizes the overall discovery process by maximizing the volume of evaluated ideas while retaining the potential for substantial improvements driven by the more powerful model.\"* (Source: PAPER)\n\n6. **AlphaEvolve is model-agnostic and improves as the base LLM improves.** PAPER §2.3: *\"Although AlphaEvolve is model-agnostic, in ablations we observe that AlphaEvolve performs increasingly better as the underlying LLM improves.\"* (Source: PAPER)\n\n## The evolutionary loop / pipeline components\n\n7. **The pipeline has four named components plus a controller loop.** PAPER (Figure 2 / §2 architecture) names them: **Prompt sampler**, **LLMs ensemble**, **Evaluators pool**, **Program database**, driven by a **Distributed Controller Loop**. (Source: PAPER)\n\n8. **The end-to-end loop, in DeepMind's words (PAPER §2 overview):** *\"AlphaEvolve then initiates an evolutionary loop. The Prompt sampler uses programs from the Program database to construct rich prompts (Section 2.2). Given these prompts, the LLMs generate code modifications (diffs), which are applied to create new programs (Section 2.3). These are then scored by Evaluators (Section 2.4), and promising solutions are registered back into the Program database (Section 2.5), driving the iterative [process].\"* (Source: PAPER)\n\n9. **The core loop is captured as three lines of pseudocode.** PAPER (Distributed Controller Loop figure):\n   ```\n   diff = llm.generate(prompt)\n   child_program = apply_diff(parent_program, diff)\n   results = evaluator.execute(child_program)\n   ```\n   (Source: PAPER)\n\n10. **Blog-level restatement of the loop.** BLOG: *\"Together, these models propose computer programs that implement algorithmic solutions as code... AlphaEvolve verifies, runs and scores the proposed programs using automated evaluation metrics.\"* (Source: BLOG)\n\n11. **The prompt is assembled from prior solutions sampled from the database plus instructions.** PAPER §2.2: *\"This prompt comprises multiple previously discovered solutions sampled from the program database, as well as system instructions on how to propose changes to a particular solution.\"* It also supports explicit context, stochastic formatting, rendered evaluation results, and \"meta prompt evolution.\" (Source: PAPER)\n\n## Code editing mechanism (diffs vs. full rewrites; codebase scope)\n\n12. **The default mutation mechanism is diff-based SEARCH/REPLACE blocks.** PAPER §2.3, \"Output format\": *\"When AlphaEvolve asks an LLM to modify existing code, especially within larger codebases, it requests the changes to be provided as a sequence of diff blocks in a specific format:\"* — the format being\n    ```\n    <<<<<<< SEARCH\n    # Original code block to be found and replaced\n    =======\n    # New code block to replace the original\n    >>>>>>> REPLACE\n    ```\n    *\"the code between <<<<<<< SEARCH and ======= is the exact segment to match in the current program version... This allows for targeted updates to specific parts of the code.\"* (Source: PAPER)\n\n13. **Full rewrites are an alternative configuration for short code.** PAPER §2.3: *\"In cases where the code being evolved is very short, or when a complete rewrite is more appropriate than a small modification, AlphaEvolve can be configured to instruct the LLM to output the entire code block directly, rather than using the diff format.\"* (Source: PAPER)\n\n14. **It edits within whole files/codebases, marking blocks to evolve with `EVOLVE-BLOCK` markers.** PAPER §2.1 / Figure 3: the user provides a file \"with blocks marked for evolution\" (`# EVOLVE-BLOCK-START` ... `# EVOLVE-BLOCK-END`) plus a special `evaluate` function; *\"it requests the changes... especially within larger codebases.\"* Levels of abstraction vary by problem — single functions up to bespoke search algorithms. (Source: PAPER)\n\n15. **It makes direct changes to code (not just single functions).** PAPER abstract: *\"AlphaEvolve orchestrates an autonomous pipeline of LLMs, whose task is to improve an algorithm by making direct changes to the code.\"* (Source: PAPER)\n\n## Evaluators / scoring\n\n16. **Candidates are scored by executing a user-provided evaluation function `h` returning scalar metrics.** PAPER §2.4: *\"each new solution proposed by the LLMs is automatically evaluated. In principle, this process amounts to simply executing the user-provided evaluation function h on the generated solution.\"* The function is \"a Python function, called evaluate, with a fixed input/output signature.\" (Source: PAPER)\n\n17. **Evaluation supports a cascade (cheap-to-expensive filtering).** PAPER §2.4: *\"Evaluation cascade (hypothesis testing): the user can specify ensembles of test cases of increasing difficulty, such that new solutions are evaluated on the next stage only if they achieve sufficiently promising results in all earlier stages.\"* (Source: PAPER)\n\n18. **Optional LLM-generated feedback can add scores (e.g., for simplicity).** PAPER §2.4: properties \"difficult to capture precisely in the user-provided evaluation function... can be graded using separate LLM calls and added to the dictionary of scores to steer evolution.\" (Source: PAPER)\n\n19. **AlphaEvolve supports multi-objective optimization, which it finds helps even a single target metric.** PAPER §2.4 \"Multiple scores\": *\"we find that even if one metric is of particular interest, optimizing for multiple metrics often improves results for the single target metric.\"* (Source: PAPER)\n\n## Program database / selection algorithm\n\n20. **The selection/storage algorithm is a combination of MAP-Elites and island-based population models.** PAPER §2.5: *\"In AlphaEvolve, the evolutionary database implements an algorithm that is inspired by a combination of the MAP elites algorithm [74] and island-based population models [83, 97].\"* Its goal: *\"balancing exploration and exploitation, to continuously improve the best programs while maintaining diversity.\"* (Source: PAPER)\n\n21. **The blog's plainer description of the database's role:** the programs database *\"implements an evolutionary algorithm that determines which programs will be used for future prompts.\"* (Source: BLOG)\n\n## Distributed / async pipeline and overall throughput orientation\n\n22. **It's an asyncio-based asynchronous pipeline of controller + LLM samplers + evaluation nodes, optimized for throughput.** PAPER §2.6: *\"AlphaEvolve is implemented as an asynchronous computational pipeline (using the asyncio Python library)... the asynchronous pipeline comprises a controller, LLM samplers, and evaluation nodes. The entire pipeline is optimized for throughput (rather than the speed of any one particular computation), in order to maximize the number of ideas that can be proposed and evaluated within a specific overall computation budget.\"* (Source: PAPER)\n\n23. **AlphaEvolve is a successor to / generalization of FunSearch.** PAPER §1 (Table 1) contrasts it with FunSearch [83] (which evolved a single function with fast ≤20-min single-CPU evaluation), whereas AlphaEvolve evolves entire code files and \"can evaluate for hours, in parallel, on accelerators.\" (Source: PAPER)\n\n## Context note for the local build\nThe key architectural lesson transferable to the Yogi research arm (M6 population + selection): AlphaEvolve's selection is **MAP-Elites + island-model** over a program database, with a **prompt sampler** that builds prompts from sampled parents, an **LLM ensemble split by cost/quality** (cheap/fast model for breadth + expensive model for occasional depth), **diff-based mutation (SEARCH/REPLACE)** as the default mutation surface, and an **evaluation cascade** that prunes cheaply before expensive scoring. All four are in PAPER §2.\n\n### Source URLs\n- DeepMind blog: https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/\n- DeepMind white paper PDF: https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf\n\nOne caveat: WebFetch could not parse the PDF (binary streams), so I extracted the text locally with `pdftotext` from the cached copy DeepMind served — all paper quotes above are verbatim from that extraction, with section numbers as printed in the document."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2298,"cache_read_input_tokens":23917,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2298,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcG28CZrTqn1ZgidBnxr3","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"861dea32-21ca-464d-9816-af1c72a64760","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:36:23.538Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
